  <mainDescription>&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    In order to achieve their goals, organisations increasingly relie on the realisation of projects and PM² is a guide
    that can help them manage projects in an effective way.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>Who&lt;/strong> has developed the PM² Guide?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    This project management standard has been produced and published by the Centre of Excellence in Project Management (CoE
    PM²), an entity of the European Commission.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>What&lt;/strong> does the PM² Guide provide to its users?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    The PM² Guide provides the following to its users:
&lt;/p>
&lt;ol>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            A project governance structure&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            Process guidelines&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            Artefact templates&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            Guidelines for using the artefacts&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            A set of effective mindsets
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>When&lt;/strong> was the Open PM² Guide created?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    The current edition of the PM² guide (v 3.0) was published in October 2018.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>Where&lt;/strong> can the PM² Guide be deployed?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    When the Centre of Excellence in Project Management (CoEPM²) of the European Commission created this project management
    standard, its objective was to respond to the needs of European Union institutions and projects but, any institutions
    can also use this guide to effectively manage their projects.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>How&lt;/strong> does the PM² Guide help organisations effectively manage their projects?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    The PM² guide emphasises among others the importance of close collaboration between two groups, namely, the requestor
    side and the provider side. During the entire project, the requestor side (the Project Owner, the Business Manager ane
    the Business Implementation Group) work hand in hand with the provider side (the Solution Provider, the Project Manager
    and the Project Core team) in order to achieve the project objectives. Also important in PM² are transition and
    business implementation plans, plans whose execution ensures project deliverables are seemlessly integrated in the
    client's operations.
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    &lt;strong>How many&lt;/strong> stakeholder categories do we find in a PM² project?
&lt;/p>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    Rather than instrumental, projects are sociopolitical processes in which politics and conflicting interests among
    stakeholders are commonplace, hence the importance of adopting a multiple stakeholder perspective when discussing
    concepts such as project objectives and success criteria. According to the PM² Guide, project stakeholders can be
    grouped into the following five (5) categories or layers:
&lt;/p>
&lt;ol>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Business Governing Layer&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Steering Layer&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Directing Layer&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Managing Layer&lt;br />
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
    &lt;li>
        &lt;div align=&quot;justify&quot;>
            The Performing Layer
        &lt;/div>
    &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;p align=&quot;justify&quot;>
    In addition to these categories, there is another called Project Support Team and this comprises a variety of optional
    roles.&lt;br />
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
